    {
      "id": "1518147437213257848",
      "type": "Reply",
      "timestamp": "2026-06-21T06:55:54.847+00:00",
      "timestampEdited": null,
      "callEndedTimestamp": null,
      "isPinned": false,
      "content": "Having just spent a lot of time with Tim and asking many questions, I feel like I can say a few things. \n@tnt is quite spot on and in that light Global Foundries seems like the best choice overall. \nFor one, price, and GF also has a lot more resources when it comes to things that are most beneficial regarding more goals in the general open source silicon ecosystem. \nPart of Tim's thesis (and I also agree) is that it's beneficial to have for profit institutions involved and benefiting from open silicon and the tools/people/etc. surrounding it. \nTaking all these into consideration Skywater is less suited in many areas and doesn't take into account the logistics required to support another foundry. For these and other reasons, I would say to stick to GF only, and this is coming from someone who lives a few hours from them.",
      "author": {
        "id": "756011607603019777",
        "name": "anfroholic",
        "discriminator": "0000",
        "nickname": "Andrew Wingate",
        "color": null,
        "isBot": false,
